<div id="banner">
	<h1>Kragen Explains the Sunlight Effect</h1>
</div>

<div class="content">
<p>Thanks to Kragen Sitaker for sending me feedback about my <a href="000594">sunlight experience</a>. He writes:</p><blockquote>This is painful at first because too much light enters your eye; after a while, your iris adjusts, your pupil shrinks, and the light level in your eye falls to a tolerable level.  One side-effect of your pupil shrinking is that your depth of field increases.  (If you&#8217;re a photographer, you know this happens when you go to a smaller aperture (f/stop).)  Intuitively, your eye is becoming more like a pinhole camera, for which everything is in focus.</blockquote><p>Aha! I&#8217;ll have to work this into my worldview some more&#8230;</p>

<p class="posted">posted September 14, 2002 08:09 PM (<a class="category" href="http://www.aaronsw.com/weblog/cat_personal">Personal</a>)  <a href="000596" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>

